§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Can a set have no elements? ⦉
⦉

§ Definition ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Sure. ⦉

  ‖ A set exists by the principle of existence (see␣
    <a href='/sheets/sets.html'>
      ‖ Sets ⦉
    </a>
    ); denote it by $A$. ⦉

  ‖ Specify elements (see␣
    <a href='/sheets/set_specification.html'>
      ‖ Set Specification ⦉
    </a>
    ) of any set that exists using the universally false
    statement $x ≠ x$. ⦉

  ‖ We denote that set by $\Set{x ∈ A}{x ≠ x}$. ⦉

  ‖ It has no elements. ⦉

  ‖ In other words, $(∀ x)(x \not ∈ A)$. ⦉

  ‖ The principle of extension (see␣
    <a href='/sheets/set_equality.html'>
      ‖ Set Equality ⦉
    </a>
    ) says that the set obtained is unique (contradiction).
    † ⦊
      ‖ This account will be expanded in the next edition. ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ We call the unique set with no elements the ❬empty set❭. ⦉
⦉

